 For j=i, k=0, semicolon, t_k not equal to, backslash zero, and, double ampersand, s_j double equals t_k, semicolon, j++, k++, semicolon.

30
00:07:46,080 --> 00:08:07,440
 If, open paren(t_k) double equals, quote, backslash zero, quote, closed paren, return, open paren(i), closed paren, semicolon, closed curly brace, return, open paren minus one, closed paren, semicolon, curly brace.

31
00:08:07,440 --> 00:08:21,520
 Each function has the form, name, argument list, if any, in parentheses, argument declarations, if any, open curly brace, declarations and statements, if any, closed curly brace.

32
00:08:21,520 --> 00:08:31,920
 As suggested, various parts may be absent. A minimal function is dummy, open paren, closed paren, open curly brace, closed curly brace, which does nothing.

33
00:08:31,920 --> 00:08:46,800
 A do-nothing function is sometimes useful as a placeholder during program development. The function name may also be preceded by a type if the function returns something other than an integer value. This is the topic of the next section.

34
00:08:46,800 --> 00:08:56,800
 A program is just a set of individual function definitions. Communication between the functions is, in this case, by arguments and values returned by the functions.

35
00:08:56,800 --> 00:09:07,600
 It can also be via external variables. The functions can occur in any order in the source file, and the source program can be split into multiple files, so long as no function is split.

36
00:09:07,600 --> 00:09:17,840
 The return statement is the mechanism for returning a residual value from the called function to its caller. Any expression can follow return.

37
00:09:17,840 --> 00:09:31,760
 Return, open parentheses, expression, closed parentheses. The calling function is free to ignore the return value if it wishes. Furthermore, there is no need to have an expression after the return.

38
00:09:31,760 --> 00:09:43,040
 In that case, no value is returned to the caller. Control also returns to the caller with no value when execution falls off the end of the function by reaching the right closing brace.

39
00:09:43,040 --> 00:09:51,440
 It is not illegal, but probably a sign of trouble if a function returns a value from one place and no value from another place.

40
00:09:51,440 --> 00:10:03,120
 In any case, the residual value of a function which does not return one is certain to be garbage. The C verifier lint checks for such errors.

41
00:10:03,120 --> 00:10:14,880
 Mechanics of how to compile and load a C program which resides on multiple source files vary from one system to the next. On the Unix system, for example, the CC command mentioned in Chapter 1 does the job.

42
00:10:14,880 --> 00:10:39,520
 Suppose that three functions are in three files called main.c, getline.c, and index.c. Then the command cc main.c getline.c index.c compiles the three files and places the resulting relocatable object code in files main.o, getline.o, and index.o, and loads them all into an executable file named a.out.

43
00:10:39,520 --> 00:10:52,800
 If there is an error, say in main.c, that file can be recompiled by itself and the result loaded with the previous object files with the command cc main.c getline.o index.o.

44
00:10:52,800 --> 00:11:01,680
 The CC command uses the .c suffix versus the .o suffix name and convention to distinguish source files from object files.

45
00:11:01,680 --> 00:11:18,000
 I would note that this CC example exactly as the authors wrote, it does not quite work as described in modern C compilers. If you want to compile your source code and leave the compiled object code around after the compile, you add the -c option to the compiler call.

46
00:11:18,000 --> 00:11:27,280
 Modern C compilers generally do accept multiple files with either .c or .o suffixes and can combine them into a runnable application.

47
00:11:27,280 --> 00:11:36,960
 Section 4.2, Functions Returning Non-Integers. So far, none of our programs has contained any declaration of the type of a function.

48
00:11:36,960 --> 00:11:51,440
 This is because, by default, a function is implicitly declared by its appearance in an expression or statement, such as while openparen getline openparen line comma maxline closeparen greater than zero closeparen.

49
00:11:51,440 --> 00:12:01,920
 If a name which has not been previously declared occurs in an expression and is followed by a left parenthesis, it is declared by context to be a function name.

50
00:12:01,920 --> 00:12:19,520
 Furthermore, by default, the function is assumed to return an int. Since char promotes to int in expressions, there is no need to declare functions that return char. These assumptions cover the majority of classes, including all of our examples so far.

51
00:12:19,520 --> 00:12:34,000
 I would add, that's not quite true anymore. In modern C languages, you are required to provide a type for each function. If you leave off the type for a function declaration at a minimum, you will get a stern warning message.

52
00:12:34,000 --> 00:12:43,200
 But sometimes functions do not intend to return anything at all, and so the void type was invented to indicate that a function returns nothing.

53
00:12:43,200 --> 00:12:56,800
 The rule of requiring a type on a modern function definition in C, even if it's void, allows the compiler to check to make sure all of your return values in a function match the expected return type.

54
00:12:56,800 --> 00:13:03,120
 Back to the text. But what happens if a function must return some other type?

55
00:13:03,120 --> 00:13:20,800
 Many numerical functions like square root, sine, and cosine return double. Other specialized functions return other types. To illustrate how to deal with this, let us write and use the function a to f, which converts its argument string s to its double precision floating point equivalent.

56
00:13:20,800 --> 00:13:34,960
 a to f is an extension of a to i, which we wrote versions of in chapters two and three. It handles an optional sign and decimal point and the presence or absence of either the integer or fractional part.

57
00:13:34,960 --> 00:13:43,200
 We note that this is not a high quality input conversion routine. Doing everything takes a bit more space than we care to use here in this book.

58
00:13:43,200 --> 00:13:54,080
 First, a to f must declare the type of the value it returns since it's not int. Because float is converted to double in expressions, there is no point in saying that a to f returns float.

59
00:13:54,080 --> 00:14:02,800
 We might as well make use of the extra precision and thus declare it to return double. The type name precedes the function name like this.

60
00:14:02,800 --> 00:14:17,920
 Double a to f, open parenthesis, s, close parenthesis, char, s, open square bracket, close square bracket, open curly brace, double val, comma, power, int, i, comma, sine, semicolon.

