74
00:17:37,760 --> 00:18:05,760
 while, open parenthesis, get line, open parenthesis, line, comma, max line, close parenthesis, greater than zero, close parenthesis, print f, quote, backslash t, percent, dot 2f, backslash n, comma, sum, plus equals a to f, open parenthesis, line, close parenthesis, semicolon, close curly brace.

75
00:18:05,760 --> 00:18:16,720
 That code used the plus equals side effect operator and merged the call to a to f right into the second parameter of print f.

76
00:18:16,720 --> 00:18:28,000
 The declaration, double, sum, a to f, open parenthesis, close parenthesis, says that sum is a double variable and that a to f is a function that returns a double value.

77
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:35,360
 As a mnemonic, it suggests that sum and a to f, parenthesis, dot, dot, dot, are both double precision floating point values.

78
00:18:35,360 --> 00:18:44,640
 Unless a to f is explicitly declared in both places, c assumes it returns an integer and you will get nonsense answers.

79
00:18:44,640 --> 00:18:53,560
 If a to f itself and the call to it in main aren't typed inconsistently within the same source file, it will be detected by the compiler.

80
00:18:53,560 --> 00:19:06,840
 But if, as is more likely, a to f were compiled separately, the mismatch would not be detected and a to f would return a double, which main would treat as an int and meaningless answers would result.

81
00:19:06,840 --> 00:19:09,720
 Lindt catches this error.

82
00:19:09,720 --> 00:19:16,640
 Given a to f, we could in principle write a to i to convert a string to an integer in terms of it.

83
00:19:16,640 --> 00:19:30,840
 Int, a to i, open parenthesis, close parenthesis, char, s, open square bracket, close square bracket, semicolon, open curly brace, double, a to f, open parenthesis, close parenthesis, semicolon.

84
00:19:30,840 --> 00:19:40,000
 Return, open parenthesis, a to f, close parenthesis, s, close parenthesis, close parenthesis, semicolon, close curly brace.

85
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:42,720
 Note the structure of the declarations in the return statement.

86
00:19:42,720 --> 00:19:50,640
 The value in the expression in return expression is always converted to the type of the function before the return is taken.

87
00:19:50,640 --> 00:20:03,520
 Therefore, the value of a to f, a double, is converted automatically to int when it appears in a return, since the function a to i returns an int.

88
00:20:03,520 --> 00:20:10,200
 The conversion of a floating point value to int truncates any fractional part, as we discussed in Chapter 2.

89
00:20:10,200 --> 00:20:12,440
 More on function arguments.

90
00:20:12,440 --> 00:20:17,360
 In Chapter 1, we discussed the fact that function arguments are passed by value.

91
00:20:17,360 --> 00:20:24,120
 That is, the called function receives a private, temporary copy of each argument, not its address.

92
00:20:24,120 --> 00:20:29,120
 This means that the function cannot affect the original argument in the calling function.

93
00:20:29,120 --> 00:20:36,920
 Within a function, each argument is in effect a local variable initialized to the value with which the function was called.

94
00:20:36,920 --> 00:20:43,840
 When an array name appears as an argument to a function, the location of the beginning of the array is passed.

95
00:20:43,840 --> 00:20:45,760
 Elements are not copied.

96
00:20:45,760 --> 00:20:51,080
 The function can alter elements of the array by subscripting from this location.

97
00:20:51,080 --> 00:20:55,200
 The effect is that arrays are always passed by reference.

98
00:20:55,200 --> 00:21:04,040
 In Chapter 5, we will discuss the use of pointers to permit functions to affect non-arrays in calling functions.

99
00:21:04,040 --> 00:21:06,920
 A bit of a digression.

100
00:21:06,920 --> 00:21:12,320
 Since including array as an argument passes the location or memory address of the array into the function,

101
00:21:12,320 --> 00:21:17,040
 the function can change the items in the array using array subscripts.

102
00:21:17,040 --> 00:21:23,360
 In particular, the array contents are not copied when an array is passed into a C function.

103
00:21:23,360 --> 00:21:31,280
 When we get to structs in a future chapter, we will find that the content of structs also are passed using the address of the entire struct.

104
00:21:31,280 --> 00:21:34,680
 So structs are passed by reference as well.

105
00:21:34,680 --> 00:21:44,160
 When thinking about pass by reference or pass by value, remember that a char variable is a single item similar to int and passed by value, i.e. it is copied.

106
00:21:44,160 --> 00:21:50,440
 In C, strings are arrays of characters, so they are passed by reference.

107
00:21:50,440 --> 00:21:55,080
 Python follows this design for the same efficiency reason as C.

108
00:21:55,080 --> 00:22:02,640
 Normal single variables like int or float are copied before being passed into a function and therefore passed by value.

109
00:22:02,640 --> 00:22:10,680
 Collections like list or dict are passed into functions by reference, so the contents can be changed within a function.

110
00:22:10,680 --> 00:22:15,360
 Python strings are not technically copied when being passed into a function,

111
00:22:15,360 --> 00:22:23,680
 but the way assignments happen in Python make it seem like strings are passed by value, since they can never be modified.

112
00:22:23,680 --> 00:22:35,640
 You can learn more with a bit of web research, but the easy way is to imagine in Python that strings are passed by value with a clever trick to avoid requiring a copy for every function call.

113
00:22:35,640 --> 00:22:42,440
 PHP follows the same pattern of passing numbers and strings by value and passing arrays as reference.

114
00:22:42,440 --> 00:22:57,880
 PHP passes strings by value without requiring a copy, again, using clever runtime code. Because in Java, JavaScript and PHP strings are objects, of course, which we haven't discussed much yet.

115
00:22:57,880 --> 00:23:06,600
 Those languages can make sure that strings act as if they were passed by value and not passed by reference the way they are always passed in C.

116
00:23:06,600 --> 00:23:21,440
 C made decisions on its runtime based on getting the maximum performance out of the hardware of the 1970s at the expense of making it too easy to write code that overwrites memory and leads to corrupted programs that have dangerous and undefined behavior.

117
00:23:21,440 --> 00:23:38,880
 Languages like PHP, Java and JavaScript add a small amount of runtime overhead to do things like store the length of an array and make sure we programmers don't overreference the array and overwrite random bits of our program's code or data.

118
00:23:38,880 --> 00:23:45,240
 The creators of C placed more priority on speed and efficient use of memory than safety.

119
00:23:45,240 --> 00:24:02,840
 It is like driving an automobile in the rain without ABS, automatic braking system. It is fast but dangerous and should be reserved by highly skilled and very careful programmers and drivers, and those drivers should probably be on a race course.

120
00:24:02,840 --> 00:24:19,920
 By the way, back to the text. By the way, there is no entirely satisfactory way to write a portable function that accepts a variable number of arguments because there is no portable way for the called function to determine how many arguments were actually passed in a given call.

121
00:24:19,920 --> 00:24:31,640
 Thus, you can't write a truly portable function that will compute the maximum of an arbitrary number of arguments, as will the max functions that are built in to Fortran and PL1.

122
00:24:31,640 --> 00:24:41,040
 It is generally safe to deal with a variable number of arguments if the called function doesn't use an argument that was not actually supplied, and if the types are consistent.

123
00:24:41,040 --> 00:24:54,280
 printf, the most common C function with a variable number of arguments, uses information from the first argument, which is the formatting string, to determine how many other arguments are present and what their types are.

124
00:24:54,280 --> 00:25:08,080
 It fails badly if the caller does not supply enough arguments or if types are not what the first argument says. It is also non-portable and therefore must be modified for different programming environments.

125
00:25:08,080 --> 00:25:20,480
 Alternatively, if arguments are of known types, it is possible to mark the end of the argument list in some agreed upon way, such as a special argument value, often zero, that stands for the end of the arguments.

126
00:25:20,480 --> 00:25:29,640
 Interestingly, modern languages like Python, PHP, and Java, go to great lengths to make variable length argument lists work predictably and portably.

127
00:25:29,640 --> 00:25:39,680
 The syntax for variable length argument lists in these languages can be a bit obtuse at times, but at least it is allowed, documented, reliable, and portable.

128
00:25:39,680 --> 00:25:43,280
 Section four, external variables.

129
00:25:43,280 --> 00:25:49,320
 A C program consists of a set of external objects, which are either variables or functions.

130
00:25:49,320 --> 00:25:59,920
 The adjective external is used primarily in contrast to internal, which describes arguments and automatic variables defined inside functions.

131
00:25:59,920 --> 00:26:06,720
 External variables are defined outside any function and are thus potentially available to many functions.

132
00:26:06,720 --> 00:26:13,800
 Functions themselves are always external, because C does not allow functions to be defined inside other functions.

133
00:26:13,800 --> 00:26:25,720
 By default, external variables are also global, so that all references to such a variable by the same name, even from functions that are compiled separately, are references to the same thing.

134
00:26:25,720 --> 00:26:32,520
 In this sense, external variables are analogous to Fortran common or PL1 external.

135
00:26:32,520 --> 00:26:42,160
 We will later see how to define external variables and functions that are not globally available, but instead only visible within a single source file.

136
00:26:42,160 --> 00:26:51,520
 Because external variables are globally accessible, they provide an alternative to function arguments and return values for communicating data between function.

137
00:26:51,520 --> 00:26:59,760
 Any function may access an external variable by referring it to by name, if the name has been declared somehow.

138
00:26:59,760 --> 00:27:07,960
 If a large number of variables must be shared among functions, external variables are a more convenient and efficient than long argument lists.

139
00:27:07,960 --> 00:27:21,400
 As pointed out in Chapter 1, however, this reasoning should be applied with some caution, for it can have a bad effect on program structure and lead to programs with many data connections between functions.

140
00:27:21,400 --> 00:27:26,320
 A second reason for using external variables concerns initialization.

141
00:27:26,320 --> 00:27:32,760
 In particular, external arrays may be initialized, but automatic, i.e. internal arrays, may not.

142
00:27:32,760 --> 00:27:37,040
 We will treat initialization near the end of this chapter.

143
00:27:37,040 --> 00:27:41,480
 A third reason for using external variables is their scope and lifetime.

144
00:27:41,480 --> 00:27:44,480
 Automatic variables are internal to a function.

145
00:27:44,480 --> 00:27:49,800
 They come into existence when the routine is entered and disappear when it's left.

146
00:27:49,800 --> 00:27:52,480
 External variables, on the other hand, are permanent.

147
00:27:52,480 --> 00:27:57,640
 They do not come and go, so they retain values from one function invocation to the next.

148
00:27:57,640 --> 00:28:10,600
 Thus, if two functions must share some data, yet neither calls the other, it is often most convenient if the shared data is kept in external variables rather than passed in and out via arguments.

149
00:28:10,600 --> 00:28:13,920
 Let's examine this issue further with a larger example.

150
00:28:13,920 --> 00:28:19,360
 The problem is to write another calculator program better than the previous one.

151
00:28:19,360 --> 00:28:25,520
 This one permits plus, minus, asterisk, and slash, and equals.

152
00:28:25,520 --> 00:28:27,560
 Equals will print our answer.

153
00:28:27,560 --> 00:28:35,720
 Because it is somewhat easier to implement, the calculator will use reverse-polish notation instead of infix notation.

154
00:28:35,720 --> 00:28:42,560
 Reverse-polish notation is the scheme used by, for example, Hewlett-Packard pocket calculators.

155
00:28:42,560 --> 00:28:48,640
 In reverse-polish notation, each operator follows its operands.

156
00:28:48,640 --> 00:29:08,120
 An infix expression, like open parentheses 1 minus 2, close parentheses star, open parentheses 4 plus 5, close parentheses equals, is entered as 1, 2, minus, 4, 5, plus, star, equals.

157
00:29:08,120 --> 00:29:11,440
 Parentheses are not needed in reverse-polish notation.

158
00:29:11,440 --> 00:29:14,440
 The implementation is quite simple.

159
00:29:14,440 --> 00:29:17,600
 Each operand is pushed onto a stack.

160
00:29:17,600 --> 00:29:23,960
 When an operator arrives, the proper number of operands, 2 for binary operators, are popped.

161
00:29:23,960 --> 00:29:28,080
 The operator applied to them, and the result is pushed back onto the stack.

162
00:29:28,080 --> 00:29:33,800
 In the example above, 1 and 2 are pushed, then replaced by their difference, negative 1.

163
00:29:33,800 --> 00:29:38,280
 Next, 4 and 5 are pushed, then replaced by their sum, 9.

164
00:29:38,280 --> 00:29:43,720
 And then the product of negative 1 and 9, which is negative 9, replaces them on the stack.

165
00:29:43,720 --> 00:29:49,360
 And then the equal sign operator prints the top element without removing it.

166
00:29:49,360 --> 00:29:53,200
 So intermediate steps in a calculation can be checked.

167
00:29:53,200 --> 00:29:56,600
 The operations of pushing and popping a stack are trivial.

168
00:29:56,600 --> 00:30:05,840
 But by the time error detection and recovery are added, they're long enough so it's better to put each in a separate function than to repeat the code throughout the whole program.

169
00:30:05,840 --> 00:30:10,720
 And there should be a separate function for fetching the next input operator or operand.

170
00:30:10,720 --> 00:30:19,720
 Thus, the overall structure of the program is, while next operator or operand is not in the file, if it's a number, push it.

171
00:30:19,720 --> 00:30:25,040
 Else, if it's an operator, pop operands, do the operation, and push the result.

172
00:30:25,040 --> 00:30:26,920
 Else, error.

173
00:30:26,920 --> 00:30:31,200
 The main design decision that has not yet been discussed is where the stack is.

174
00:30:31,200 --> 00:30:34,600
 That is, what routines access it directly.

175
00:30:34,600 --> 00:30:41,560
 One possibility is to keep it in main and pass the stack and current stack position to the routines that push and pop it.

176
00:30:41,560 --> 00:30:44,800
 But main doesn't need to know about the variables that control the stack.

177
00:30:44,800 --> 00:30:47,160
 It should only think about pushing and popping.

178
00:30:47,160 --> 00:30:57,920
 So we have decided to make the stack and its associated information external variables accessible to push and pop, but not to main.

179
00:30:57,920 --> 00:31:00,920
 Translating this outline to code is easy enough.

