219
00:38:23,880 --> 00:38:46,200
 As discussed in chapter one, a variable is external if it is defined outside the body of any function. Thus the stack and stack pointer, which must be shared by push, pop and clear, are defined outside the three functions. But if main itself does not refer to the stack or stack pointer, their representation is carefully hidden.

220
00:38:46,200 --> 00:38:58,120
 Thus the code for the equal operator must use push, open paren, pop, paren, close paren, close paren, semicolon to examine the top of the stack without disturbing it.

221
00:38:58,120 --> 00:39:12,360
 Notice also that because plus and multiplication are commutative operators, the order in which the popped operands are combined is irrelevant. But for the minus and slash operators, the left and right operands must be distinguished.

222
00:39:12,360 --> 00:39:21,880
 This example code above shows why it's important to remember the KNRC rearrangement license as it applies to operators that are associative and commutative.

223
00:39:21,880 --> 00:39:38,680
 If the code for the minus operator were written push, open paren, pop, open paren, close paren, minus pop, open paren, close paren, semicolon, there is no guarantee that the left pop will run before the right pop.

224
00:39:38,680 --> 00:39:47,960
 And since these functions access global variables and have side effects, it is important to force the compiler not to rearrange the order of the function calls.

225
00:39:47,960 --> 00:40:02,680
 To force the evaluation order, the code is broken into two statements. Op2 equals pop, open paren, close paren, semicolon. Push, open paren, pop, open paren, close paren, minus op2, close paren, semicolon.

226
00:40:02,680 --> 00:40:11,560
 Now you might think that the lesson here is that the KNRC arrangement license, which was done to allow optimization and performance, is a bad idea.

227
00:40:11,560 --> 00:40:23,640
 But the more important lesson is that writing low-level utility functions like push and pop that use global variables and have side effects is a dangerous pattern in any programming language.

228
00:40:23,640 --> 00:40:33,400
 Section 4.5, scope rules. The functions and external variables that make up a C program need not all be compiled at the same time.

229
00:40:33,400 --> 00:40:40,840
 The source text of the program may be kept in several files and previously compiled routines may be loaded from libraries.

230
00:40:40,840 --> 00:40:57,000
 The two questions of interest are how are declarations written so that variables are properly declared during compilation and how are declarations set up so that all the pieces will be properly linked or connected when the program is loaded.

231
00:40:57,000 --> 00:41:02,760
 The scope of a name is the part of the program over which the name is defined.

232
00:41:02,760 --> 00:41:14,040
 For an automatic variable, declared at the beginning of a function, the scope is the function in which the name is declared and variables of the same name in different functions are unrelated.

233
00:41:14,040 --> 00:41:17,400
 The same is true of the arguments of the function.

234
00:41:17,400 --> 00:41:25,560
 The scope of an external variable lasts from the point at which it is declared in a source file to the end of that file.

235
00:41:25,560 --> 00:41:32,680
 For example, if val, sp, push, pop, and clear are defined in one file in the order shown above,

236
00:41:32,680 --> 00:41:39,320
 that is int sp equals zero, double val open square bracket max val close square bracket semicolon,

237
00:41:39,320 --> 00:41:46,280
 double push open paren f close paren open curly brace dot dot dot close curly brace, double pop

238
00:41:46,280 --> 00:41:52,440
 open paren close paren open curly brace dot dot dot close curly brace, clear open paren close paren

239
00:41:52,440 --> 00:41:59,560
 open curly brace dot dot dot close curly brace, then the variables val and sp may be used in push,

240
00:41:59,560 --> 00:42:04,040
 pop, and clear simply by naming them and no further declarations are needed.

241
00:42:04,040 --> 00:42:11,480
 On the other hand, if an external variable is to be referenced before it is defined or it is defined

242
00:42:11,480 --> 00:42:16,520
 in a different source file from the one in which it's being used, then an extern declaration is

243
00:42:16,520 --> 00:42:23,080
 mandatory. It is very important to distinguish between the declaration of an external variable

244
00:42:23,080 --> 00:42:29,320
